metadata.name: fx(haish) / the Generator #125
metadata.description:
fx(haish) is my contribution to #fxhashturnsone
fx(haish) is not a finished product
fx(haish) is a co-creation experiment
fx(haish) is a fun exploration of a mixed GenAI process

fx(haish) is my Happy Birthday to fx(hash). 

Have fun, collectors!


// HOW TO PARTICIPATE

Step 1. Mint or collect “fx(haish) - the Generator”
Step 2. Visit https://www.arqtistic.com/fx(haish) to generate your “fx(haish) - The AI City” based on your mint. You have 20 tries.
Step 3. Await further instructions.


// FURTHER INFO

This algorithm has been designed to produce images which are suitable for the subsequent AI generation. The token consists of a random number of randomly placed and sized rectangles, filled with a noise gradient pattern. In short, Diffusion AI Models thrive on noise.

The AI generation uses Stable Diffusion 1.5 through an API designed by the 330ai team (@Pixelmindai). The WebUI has been developed by Nik0gda (@AntonCebanu2). AI Prompt has been designed (by me) to produce images of Cities, but you can possibly make it do other things, if you try hard enough.

metadata.name: Sugar Skulls #32
metadata.description:
Sugar Skulls are confectionery creations traditionally made with cane sugar and decorated as part of the Mexican celebration of Day of the Dead, or Día de Muertos and All Souls Day on the first and second days of November when the dead are remembered and honored. 

So, why are they showing up here at Christmas? Well, why not?!? Christmas is a great time to enjoy a free, sweet treat while remembering those loved ones we’ve spent past Christmases with who are no longer with us.  

While most images here are of traditional sugar skulls, some lucky ones are accessorized with Santa Claus or Elf hats. 

Minting is free for as long as the project remains open. The creator may elect to close the project at any time. There is absolutely no utility promised or implied beyond the nifty artwork itself. Created for Christmas 2022.

Merry Christmas!

metadata.name: Zee  #3
metadata.description:
As wild as it is, for me the sea has something soothing. The rushing of the waves, the strong wind in your face, the salty air, the screeching of seagulls, freezing rain. At the coast it is easy to forget everything and be in the moment. The view is expansive and no matter how ominous the clouds, somewhere the sun breaks through. 

At the same time, the raging sea can be life-threatening. Many have lost their lives at sea or by the sea, some by flooding, some in the battle for peace, others in search of a better life. 

The sea, with its many faces and stories, is beautiful, terrifying and everything in between. 

#Features
Are there birds, and if so, how many?
Is it raining?
How cloudy is it?
How rough is the sea?

Generative art coded with p5js.

metadata.name: STRUCTURES #267
metadata.description:
STRUCTURES

What color do things look when you're happy?

First of all I want to dedicate this collection to all the people who paint their emotions with color, who through a chromatic range, are capable of feeling a universe of sensations most of the time inexplicable.....

 I am fascinated by how generative art creates a perfect symbiosis between art and technology, allowing through a set of algorithmic rules to give rise to compositions where shapes and colors coexist in balance, harmonized with each other that give rise to new creations.

This collection is designed to be self-contained and limited, recreating the view from different angles and phases of the day that can lead to disparate interpretations of a piece.

My work as a visual artist explores elements such as randomness and chance of linear formations and geometric gradients that broaden the spectrum to increasingly new concepts that I definitely want to explore.

I continually wonder what the geometric patterns that will emerge from my sensibility will be like and will give rise to new collections like this one, which is why I continue to investigate techniques and shapes while having fun.

"A painting is not the image of an experience, but it is the experience." Mark Rothk

metadata.name: Ruten #1
metadata.description:
◆This is an exhibition piece for Rare Effect 2022, an NFT festival that takes place at Arroz Estúdios in Lisbon from Oct. 27th - Nov. 6th 2022.


"Ruten" means in Buddhism that birth, death, and cause and effect are reincarnated. In general, it means not staying in one state but shifting and changing.

The work uses color to depict the movement and interaction of colonies of primitive organisms.
Each colony flourishes or declines, fuses or separates, transmits or takes away elements. Sometimes they even drive the other colony to death. Some colonies are large or small, bright or faded, fast-moving or slow-moving. The complex interactions of these colonies produce a variety of colors. Colonies may resonate with each other, resulting in a harmonious color, or, conversely, they may be completely disparate. The spread of pathology can also cause a loss of color.

The observer can interfere with the flow. It is a special authority in this world that governs life and death.

Press [F] key to switch to full screen mode.
Press [S] key to save image.


Modern hardware and browser hardware acceleration recommended. Chrome on a desktop with a high-end GPU is optimal.

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #222
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.
